# * commodity directive alias: tag

# ** 1. A 1:1 price directive is injected for each declared alias,
#       so values can chain across symbol/code variants.
<
commodity USD1.00
    ; alias: $

P 2024-01-01 EUR 1.10 USD

2024-06-01
    a   100 EUR @ $1.10
    b

$ hledger -f- prices
P 0000-01-01 $ USD1
P 2024-01-01 EUR USD1.10

# ** 2. The bridge lets `bal -X EUR` value $-amounts in EUR via $ -> USD -> EUR.
<
commodity USD1.00
    ; alias: $

P 2024-01-01 EUR 1.10 USD

2024-06-01
    a   100 EUR @ $1.10
    b

$ hledger -f- bal -X EUR --no-total
             100 EUR  a
            -100 EUR  b

# ** 3. Multiple aliases can be declared on a single commodity, space-separated.
#       Quoted symbols (with internal spaces or special chars) are preserved as one.
<
commodity USD1.00
    ; alias: $ "US$" USDOLLAR

2024-06-01
    a   100 USDOLLAR
    b   "US$"-50
    c

$ hledger -f- prices
P 0000-01-01 $ USD1
P 0000-01-01 US$ USD1
P 0000-01-01 USDOLLAR USD1

# ** 4. Aliases are materialised as price directives even if not used
#       in any posting.
<
commodity USD1.00
    ; alias: $ UNUSED

2024-06-01
    a   $100
    b

$ hledger -f- prices
P 0000-01-01 $ USD1
P 0000-01-01 UNUSED USD1

# ** 5. The same alias declared on two different canonicals is a finalization
#       error with a verbose message including both source positions.
<
commodity USD1.00
    ; alias: $

commodity AUD1.00
    ; alias: $

2024-01-01
    a   $100
    b

$ hledger -f- bal
>2 /Alias '\$' is declared on more than one commodity/
>=1

# ** 6. An alias matching another separately declared canonical is silently
#       allowed (a 1:1 bridge is added; the canonical commodity remains too).
<
commodity USD1.00
    ; alias: EUR

commodity EUR1.00

2024-01-01
    a   USD100
    b   EUR-100

$ hledger -f- prices
P 0000-01-01 EUR USD1

# ** 7. A self-alias (matching the directive's own symbol) is silently ignored.
<
commodity USD1.00
    ; alias: USD $

2024-01-01
    a   USD100
    b   $-100

$ hledger -f- prices
P 0000-01-01 $ USD1

# ** 8. With a commodity alias declared, valuation can convert between the
# alias and canonical symbols at a 1:1 rate.
<
commodity USD 1.00  ; alias: $

P 2024-01-01 USD 0.9 EUR

2024-06-01
    assets:cash       $100
    equity:opening

$ hledger -f- bal -X EUR --no-total
            90.0 EUR  assets:cash
           -90.0 EUR  equity:opening

# ** 9. cur:CANONICAL also matches postings written with the canonical's aliases.
<
commodity $1000.00  ; alias: USD U$

2024-01-01
    assets:cash         USD10
    equity:opening

$ hledger -f- bal cur:'\$' --no-total
               USD10  assets:cash
              USD-10  equity:opening

# ** 10. cur:ALIAS also matches postings written in the canonical commodity.
<
commodity $1000.00  ; alias: USD U$

2024-01-01
    assets:cash         $10
    equity:opening

$ hledger -f- bal cur:USD --no-total
              $10.00  assets:cash
             $-10.00  equity:opening

# ** 11. cur:OTHER_ALIAS also matches the whole group.
$ hledger -f- bal cur:'U\$' --no-total
              $10.00  assets:cash
             $-10.00  equity:opening

# ** 12. cur:REGEX is group-aware: if the regex matches any group member,
#        the whole group is matched.
$ hledger -f- bal cur:'U.*' --no-total
              $10.00  assets:cash
             $-10.00  equity:opening

# ** 13. exactcur:COMM matches only COMM, ignoring its alias group.
$ hledger -f- bal exactcur:USD --no-total

# ** 14. Separate alias groups don't bleed into each other.
<
commodity $1000.00
    ; alias: USD

commodity €1000.00
    ; alias: EUR

2024-01-01
    assets:cash         $10
    equity:opening      €-10
    assets:other        €10
    equity:opening      $-10

$ hledger -f- bal cur:USD --no-total
              $10.00  assets:cash
             $-10.00  equity:opening

# ** 15. not:cur: excludes the entire alias group.
<
commodity $1000.00
    ; alias: USD

2024-01-01
    a   $10
    b   $-10

2024-01-02
    a   USD20
    b   USD-20

$ hledger -f- bal not:cur:USD --no-total

# ** 16. cur: in auto posting rules is also alias-aware.
<
commodity $1000.00  ; alias: USD

= expenses cur:'\$'
    (fees)  $1

2024-01-01
    expenses:food      USD10
    assets:cash

$ hledger -f- bal --auto fees
               $1.00  fees
--------------------
               $1.00  

# ** 17. An alias which also has its own commodity directive (typically to
#        set its display style independently) is merged into one alias
#        group. Queries are symmetric regardless of which symbol is used.
<
commodity USD1,000.00
    ; alias: $

commodity $1,000.00

2024-01-01
    a   USD10
    b   $-10

$ hledger -f- bal cur:USD --no-total
            USD10.00  a
             $-10.00  b

# ** 18. Same scenario but querying via the alias symbol: still matches both.
<
commodity USD1,000.00
    ; alias: $

commodity $1,000.00

2024-01-01
    a   USD10
    b   $-10

$ hledger -f- bal 'cur:\$' --no-total
            USD10.00  a
             $-10.00  b

# ** 19. The merge is symmetric under reversed declaration order: declaring
#        $ as canonical (with USD as alias) plus a standalone USD directive
#        yields the same group.
<
commodity $1,000.00
    ; alias: USD

commodity USD1,000.00

2024-01-01
    a   USD10
    b   $-10

$ hledger -f- bal cur:USD --no-total
            USD10.00  a
             $-10.00  b

# ** 20. Chained alias declarations form one transitively-closed group:
#        USD -> $ -> USDOLLAR are all interchangeable for queries.
<
commodity USD1,000.00
    ; alias: $

commodity $1,000.00
    ; alias: USDOLLAR

2024-01-01
    a   USD10
    b   USDOLLAR-10

$ hledger -f- bal cur:USD --no-total
            USD10.00  a
         USDOLLAR-10  b

